@yzhliu this PR is not just about x86 conv schedules, but also contains some change I made to run a whole network run faster in conjunction with NNVM.

I should also mention that my schedule is optimized for my use case (input size being power of two, all conv are 3x3, etc..). In particular, I didn't optimize my schedules for imagenet workload at all. Nonetheless, it should be better than the current x86 schedule (which is mostly empty). 

The idea is @yzhliu or some others from community will improve on it, to make it faster on a wide range of workloads, including imagenet.

@thefiddler I am using unet style network with tvm/nnvm and have no issue at all.

I don't know about keras, but [this line](https://github.com/retinai/nnvm/blob/f3cb3d2472cdedbd31ca4cb049d4fafdec91a8b3/tests/python/frontend/keras/test_forward.py#L224) seems fishy to me.

tvm doesn't support NHWC layout at the moment, and the input should be 4d. If you set the input shape to tvm as (1, 3, 256, 256) it should work. (don't know if keras frontend does the input shape conversion automatically)

I changed the dtype of `offset` to Int64 rather than the buffer.dtype because Offset is just a number to describe offset of the buffer in the code of 

    Expr alloc_size = make_const(Int(64),(total_bits + type_bits - 1) / type_bits);

so this argument should always be int64 or uint64

the current implementation can be seen in SimplifyInference.cc file in nnvm/src/compiler folder
